Dear Hiring Team, 

It is with great pleasure that I submit my candidacy for the Full Stack Software Engineer role with Tools for Humanity. I bring over three years of professional experience across full-stack web applications, developer APIs, RESTful APIs, distributed systems, and AI-agent workflows, along with a strong academic foundation as a Master of Science in Computer Science graduate from Pace University, NY.

Through my experience across engineering roles, I have built production-grade systems aligned with TFH's need for a JavaScript/TypeScript SDK, partner integrations, backend services, and user-facing web components. At Sperse, I drove Web SDK Development and API Development for a public-facing JavaScript/TypeScript SDK and developer APIs, refactoring 500+ operations into typed dispatchers and replacing 60+ RESTful APIs with documented contracts. I also designed distributed systems with LangGraph, LangChain, Langfuse, and FastAPI, routing requests to 40+ sub-agents, and built task-scoped routing for Web SDKs, reference applications, and Partner Integrations that improved tool-selection accuracy by 90%. At Qualitest, I optimized PostgreSQL database interactions behind RESTful APIs, delivered Web Application Development with React, Spring Boot, and D3.js for user-facing web components and client-side application logic, and orchestrated backend services with AWS Step Functions and AWS Lambda across 100K+ weekly executions. That mix of server-side development, web application work, and documented integration contracts maps directly to World ID's partner-facing API, SDK, and reference implementation needs.

My research and project work reinforces the communication and technical design responsibilities of the role. At Pace Artificial Intelligence Lab, I built agent-evaluation pipelines with LLM judges and reward models, implemented a LangGraph evaluation workflow that increased tool-call success by 50%, and supported cross-functional collaboration by translating reliability data, failure modes, and technical concepts into prompt, API, and workflow design guidance. In Dark Factory, I built a TypeScript developer-facing orchestrator for distributed systems and exposed reference implementations with typed task contracts, backend service boundaries, and integration tooling. I would bring that same rigor to hands-on technical design, code review, and collaboration with product, design, partner, and engineering stakeholders on the World ID ecosystem.

I have always been passionate about technology that is built for humans in the age of AI, especially privacy-preserving proof of human and open, decentralized infrastructure. Tools for Humanity's work on World - a real human network that helps people and applications distinguish humans from AI online while supporting human-first experiences - is the kind of mission where developer experience and product reliability matter at protocol scale. I would love to discuss my interest in this position with your team and can be reached at #ph or #eml. Thank you for your time and consideration, I look forward to connecting!

